Eclipse comes with a bunch of plugins call PDE, that helps you
make a plugin.  In the wizard, steps are presented to create a simple
Java plugin.  Once this is done, add the extension in your plugin.xml
as you described in your original post and make a new class

package org.mydomain;
import ...;
public class MyCompilerErrorParser implements IErrorParser {
  pubic boolean processLine(String line, ErrorParserManager eoParser){
    /// your processing.
  }
}

 <extension
         id="MyCompilerErrorParser"
         name="My Compiler Error Parser"
         point="org.eclipse.cdt.core.ErrorParser">
      <errorparser
            class="org.mydomain.CompilerErrorParser">
      </errorparser>
 </extension>

To make a plugin it is not a bug that relates to the CDT.
Scaling down the severity of this PR.

I found a fix for this issue.  As I suspected it was trivial, but it would have 
been nice to have a better idea as to where to start looking for an answer.

When creating a custom error parser class, you must have two constructors and a 
processLine method.  The first constructor should be empty.  The second 
constructor should have the following code:

public CompilerErrorParser(IPluginDescriptor descriptor) {
    super(descriptor); 
    plugin = this;
}

